## The Operational Challenge

Your business is growing. Operations worked at 50 orders a day. At 200 orders a day, the cracks are showing. At 500, something will break.

A company's operational infrastructure defines its growth ceiling. Without designed, documented systems, teams operate reactively, relying on heroics to handle volume spikes. Scaling operations requires replacing manual check-ins with live-ops dashboards and establishing standard operating procedures that survive team turnover.

## Real-World Impact & Metrics

In our client engagements at Redevise, we regularly design and deploy these solutions. For example, when partnering with a fast-growing team in 2024, we ran an operations audit. They were processing 150 orders a day. They wanted to scale to 500. The audit found three single points of failure. Two workflows that would break at 250 orders. One tool that could not handle the volume.

We fixed the three issues. The cost was $18,000. The client scaled to 500 orders a day without disruption. Without the audit, the scaling would have produced three months of operational chaos.

The teams that audit before scaling are the ones that scale smoothly. The teams that audit after are the ones that scale painfully.

Map the workflows. Identify the single points. Measure the capacity. Fix the weaknesses. Then scale.

### Performance Comparison

| Metric | Before Redevise | After Redevise | Improvement |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Volume Deviation | Baseline | Optimized | Optimized |

> **Strategic Takeaway:** An operations audit is a structural review of your operations before the volume breaks them. Not after. Before. A comprehensive diagnostic audit should focus on three critical dimensions: Map the [workflows](/process). Every [workflow](/process). From order to delivery. From ticket to resolution. From hire to productivity. Write down every step. Identify the single points of failure. The person who is the only one who knows how to do something. The tool that has no backup. The process that stops when one person is out. Measure the capacity. How much volume can the current system handle. Not the people. The system. The system capacity is lower than you think.

